    publisher = {ACM},
    doi = {10.1145/73393.73397},
    abstract = {The range searching problems which allow partition trees where every query enters only a sublinear number of nodes are characterized as those with finite Vapnik - Chervonenk is dimension.The concrete combinatorial bounds obtained imply—among others — that every set of n points in the planecan be stored in an Ο(n) space data structure which allows triangle counting queries in Ο(√n· log3n) time, andcan be stored in an Ο(n · log n) space data structure which allows disk counting queries in Ο(√n· log3n) time; the preprocessing time for the data structures is polynomial. Recent results by Chazelle entail that these bounds for space and query time are optimal up to polylog — factors.},
